snippet.textDisplay: I work in the private sector and I have access to some of the more advanced tools available.  From a license plate you can obtain: name, dob, ssn, credit history, previous addresses back to birth, driver licenses, fishing licenses, certifications, degrees, voter registration, political party, previous relationships (girlfriends/boyfriends), business partners, criminal record, any prior e-mail address, social media account, and employment history.  The crazier part is any one of those individual items can be used to obtain the rest.  Also, any of these companies or individuals associated can also have their info pulled.  Naturally, it has pretty strict access, but it's definitely scary, nonetheless.  There is no privacy, unfortunately.

snippet.textDisplay: So for those people who are worried that he was able to get the first 3  of some ones social security number, that's honestly as simple as figuring out where some one was born. Small states (population size) like wyoming, Alaska, Hawaii, montana, ect are assigned one 3 digit starter for the entire states population. The last 4 are commonly used by people with as loose a security as phone companies, and the middle 2 only have 100 possible combinations, and are also linked to what hospital you were born in. Getting some ones social security information is remarkably simple if you know them well.

snippet.textDisplay:
In the UK, just looking at the license plate will tell you instantly the area in which the vehicle was registered when first bought and whether the vehicle was introduced earlier or later in a particular year. That's with the first 4 characters while the last 3 are random.

You can also search these vehicle plates online and easily find its MOT history (compulsory yearly inspection of vehicles in the UK). So looking at the mileage can be discarded when the licence plate can be searched online to find the reliability of the vehicle. I'm so happy that the UK is an easy country to live in to find cars(although insurance is crazy expensive for young drivers)
